@node "Introduction" "FuLLeD Guide - Introduction"

@{b}
@{fg shine}@{u}                                                                            @{uu}@{fg text}

  INTRODUCTION                                                        0A
@{u}                                                                            @{uu}
@{ub}


What is "FuLLeD"? The FAMEFuLLeD.FIM is a FIM-Door for the "Final Amiga
Mailbox Engine", @{" FAME " link "Contact" 0}. It is a fullscreen editor with many functions in
it. In counterpart to normal editors you are now able EDIT your written
lines quite similar to normal editors like CygnusEd or stuff like that!
You can mark lines, copy them and cut them. Users can even create their own
Macros and save their own configuration! The FuLLeD supports word wrap
forwards and - this is really new! - BACKWARDS. You can use multiple screens
for eg. replying messages and many things more.
Most of the commands are compatible to the Emacs 19.xx standard, so internet
freaks can use the FuLLeD without any problems. For further commad details
please take a look at @{" chapter two " link "Standard Commands" 0}! 8)


@endnode


@node "Disclaimer" "FuLLeD Guide - Disclaimer"

@{b}
@{fg shine}@{u}                                                                            @{uu}@{fg text}

  DISCLAIMER                                                          0B
@{u}                                                                            @{uu}
@{ub}

This program is still under construction! That means it can still cause
- perhaps in some cases very SERIOUS - errors that can - under even much
more strange cases - destroy your hardware or some shit like that! It never
hapend yet but you are warned! EVERYTHING is possible in our strange world
and I'm *NOT* responsible for it! 8) So use this program at your own risk!

(That have to be said coz i like my head...)

Neverless, if there are REALLY some strange bugs in it, TELL @{" ME " link "Contact" 0}! I will
correct them as fast as possible. (But take a look in the @{" Known bugs " link "Known Bugs" 0} page
first...)

@endnode


@node "Distribution" "FuLLeD Guide - Distribution"

@{b}
@{fg shine}@{u}                                                                            @{uu}@{fg text}

  DISTRIBUTION                                                        0C
@{u}                                                                            @{uu}
@{ub}


The FuLLeD is distributed with the FAME packet because it's one of the basic
parts of it. You can also get the latest version at the FAME distribution
site:

           Punishment INC. BBS - Node 1   -> (+49-30) 694 84 70

                                 Node 2   -> (+49-30) 694 85 70

The FuLLeD is distributed under the princip of shareware that means: Use it!
And if you like it, buy it! When you become a registered user of FAME you
will be automatically registered to the FuLLeD, too. A single registration
without FAME will be *NOT* possible!

For further informations, contact @{" ME " link "Contact" 0}!


@endnode


@node "Requirements" "FuLLeD Guide - Installation requirements"

@{b}
@{fg shine}@{u}                                                                            @{uu}@{fg text}

  INSTALLATION REQUIREMENTS                                           1A
@{u}                                                                            @{uu}
@{ub}


The FuLLeD requires Amiga OS 2.0 or better.

Because of some essential assigns and directories, the full FAME package
have to be installed first.

@endnode


@node "Step by step" "FuLLeD Guide - Step by step installation"

@{b}
@{fg shine}@{u}                                                                            @{uu}@{fg text}

  INSTALLATION - STEP BY STEP                                         1B
@{u}                                                                            @{uu}
@{ub}


The FuLLeD installation is quite easy:

    1.: Create a new diretory in your doors:(/FAME) directory.
        E.g. Doors:FAME/FAMEFuLLeD, it's the default one.
        (Not essential but the better way because of the FuLLeD making
        use of mutiple subdirectories. Yust for prevention of brain dead
        sysops beeing too much confused about their doors: diretory...)

    2.: Copy the main program "FAMEFuLLeD.FIM" to this created directory.

    3.: Create the following subdiretories:

            - Help          (Online help files)
            - Scripts       (for the user-defined scripts)
            - UserConfig    (for the users configuration)

    4.: Start the @{"SystemEditor" link "SystemEditor.guide/Main"}.

    5.: Go to the Doors screen.

    6.: Enter the following things:

            Door call name  : "FULLED"
            CMD-Toggle      : "SYSCMD"
            Door path       : "FAME:Doors/FAME/FAMEFuLLeD/FAMEFuLLeD.FIM"
                              (or YOUR path if it differs...)
            Stack size      : 0 (that's MY problem.. 8) )
            Access level    : 0 (that's YOUR problem...)
            Priority        : 0
            Password        : <none>
            Name at Server  : "FuLLeD v2.9"
            Internal        : OFF
            Menu (Beware)   : OFF
            Command allow   : NR, NC, CF, SR, SC, AR, AC, RD
            Mod. Type       : FIM, Multi Node

    7.: Save it!

That it should be...


@endnode


@node "Standard commands" "FuLLeD Guide - Standard commands"

@{b}
@{fg shine}@{u}                                                                            @{uu}@{fg text}

  STANDARD COMMANDS                                                   2A
@{u}                                                                            @{uu}
@{ub}


    Ctrl-A :    (go begin)

                Jump to the begin of the line. On console screen the same
                result can be reached by pressing Shift-<LEFT>.

    Ctrl-B :    (go back)

                Step back to the previous character. It's the same as
                pressing <LEFT>.

    Ctrl-C :    (command help)

                Show the command help page of the stanard commands.

    Ctrl-D :    (page down)

                Scroll one page down or jump to the last line if the actual
                page is also the last one. Same as Shift-<DOWN>.

    Ctrl-E :    (go end)

                Jump to the end of line. On console screen the same result
                can be reached by pressing Shift-<RIGHT>.

    Ctrl-F :    (go forward)

                Goes to the next character, same as pressing <RIGHT>.

    Ctrl-G :    (jump to line)

                Opens a dialog asking for a line number and jumps to it.

    Ctrl-H :    (erase)

                Erases the character under the cursor.

    Ctrl-I :    (tabulator)

                Emulates a tabulator by inserting four spaces.

    Ctrl-J :    (info)

                Opens an information screen.

    Ctrl-K :    (kill line)

                Kills the actual line and copies it to the yank-buffer.
                The old yank buffer will be OVERWRITEN, killing concerning
                lines is possible. See also Ctrl-Y.

    Ctrl-L :    (redraw screen)

                Redraws the complete screen.

    Ctrl-M :    (return)

    Ctrl-N :    (next line)

                Jumps to the next line, same as <DOWN>.

    Ctrl-O :    (change view)

                Jumps to the other view. Only possible in multiscreen mode.

    Ctrl-P :    (previous line)

                Jumps to the previous line, same as <UP>.

    Ctrl-Q :    (quit/abort)

                Aborts the actual message.

    Ctrl-R :    (read file)

                Loads a new file, for internal use only.

    Ctrl-S :    (save/quit)

                Saves the message and leaves the editor.

    Ctrl-T :    (go top)

                Jumps to the top of the message.

    Ctrl-U :    (page up)

                Scolls one page up or jumps to the first line if the actual
                page is also the top one. Same as Shift-<UP>.

    Ctrl-V :    (switch view)

                Switches the sysops page on/off if nessecary.

    Ctrl-W :    (copy line)

                Copies the first line of the lower view to the upper one.
                It's designed for the multiscreen reply mode.

    Ctrl-X :    (extended)

                Starts the extended command set.

    Ctrl-Y :    (yank line(s))

                Yanks the killed lines. See also Ctrl-K. TIP: Just try out
                these two functions before using them. They are similar
                to the Emacs functions.

    Ctrl-Z :    (go bottom)

                Go to the bottom of the text.


@endnode


@node "Extended commands" "FuLLeD Guide - Extended commands"

@{b}
@{fg shine}@{u}                                                                            @{uu}@{fg text}

  EXTENDED COMMANDS                                                   2B
@{u}                                                                            @{uu}
@{ub}


Every extended command starts by pressing Ctrl-X. All keys are case
sensitive!


    Ctrl-C :    (extended command help)

                Shows the extended command help page.

    Ctrl-F :    (flush)

                Flushes the yank buffer.

    Ctrl-L :    (screenlines)

                Opens a dialog asking you for your new screenlength.

    Ctrl-S :    (save/quit append)

                Save/quit message with appending a file.

    Ctrl-V :    (verbose)

                Switch on/off verbose mode. In verbose mode horizontal
                and vertical position will be displayed.

    0 - 9  :    (start macro)

                Starts the macro 0 to 9.

    ?      :    (options)

                Opens the options screen.

    B, b   :    (set border offset)

                Sets the temorary border offset of the middle border in
                multiscreen mode.

    C, c   :    (swap split)

                Swaps the upper and the lower view.

    D, d   :    (multiscreen mode)

                Opens/closes the second view.

    E, e   :    (execute macro)

                Starts the start or end macro, just for testing them.

    F      :    (start search)

                Starts searching a string.

    H, h   :    (help pages)

                Shows the commands help pages.

    M, m   :    (edit macro)

                Starts the macro edit screen for macro 0 to 9.

    O, o   :    (show buffer)

                Displays the yank buffer.

    Q, q   :    (abort message)

                Abort message, same as Ctrl-Q but for XON/XOFF-Users,
                because CTRl-Q is XON.

    S      :    (save/quit append)

                Save/quit message with appending a file.

    W, w   :    (move up)

                Append the lower display to the upper one. This function
                is designed for the multiscreen reply mode to snap the
                whole original message.

    f      :    (continue search)

                Continues searching with the old keyword.

    s      :    (save/quit)

                Saves the message and quits the editor. This is an imple-
                mentation for XON/XOFF-Users because Ctrl-S is XOFF.


@endnode



@node "Configuration" "FuLLeD Guide - User configuration"

@{b}
@{fg shine}@{u}                                                                            @{uu}@{fg text}

  USER CONFIGURATION                                                  2C
@{u}                                                                            @{uu}
@{ub}


The user has the possibility to make his own configuration for FuLLeD.
The configuration screen is opend by pressing Ctrl-X "?".

Screenshot:

==FuLL-eD=v2.9,=(c)1996=by=BeatniK=/=(tRSi/F-iNNOVAtiON)===FAME=Version=======

                                   OPTiONS!


    (1)Start Macro         : OFF            (2)End Macro           : OFF
    (3)Multi screen replies: OFF            (4)Verbose mode        : OFF
    (5)Partreply character : >              (6)Normal reply char   : <NONE>
    (7)Border offset       : 10





                              (s)ave    (a)bort!


                              Please select > <!




==Press=Ctrl-C=for=Commands!=======(Options)==================================


    KEY:  |  DESCRIPTION:
    ------+-------------------------------------------------------------------
          |
    "1"   |  Activate/deactivate the start macro.
          |
    "2"   |  Activate/deactivate the end macro.
          |
    "3"   |  Activates the multiscreen reply mode. If you reply a message,
          |  the second view will be opend showing the original text. You
          |  can snap single lines from this text by pressing Ctrl-W or snap
          |  the whole text by pressing Ctrl-X w.
          |
    "4"   |  Toggles the verbose mode. In verbose mode, the horizontal and
          |  vertical cursor position is displayed.
          |
    "5"   |  You can define a character here wich is inserted in front of
          |  every line of the original text if you are replying a message.
          |  This is the character beeing inserted in multiscreen reply mode.
          |
    "6"   |  This is the same as No. 5 but for normal replies.
          |
    "7"   |  Here you can define a default middle border offset for multi
          |  screen mode. The value "0" will devide the screen equal pieces,
          |  values bigger than zero will expand the upper view, values less
          |  than zero the lower one.
          |
    "s"   |  Save this settings.
          |
    "a"   |  Abort option editing.



@endnode



